nd Crosses of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the White Lion]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Gregory the Great]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Yugoslav Crown]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Romanian Academy]]\n[[Category:People from S\u0103cele]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Senate of Romania]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Crown (Italy)]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Culture]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Labor]]\n[[Category:Inmates of Sighet prison]]\n[[Category:Romanian people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Romanian detention]]\n[[Category:Twin people from Romania]]\n", "text_old": "{{citation style|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Alexandru I. Lapedatu\n|image          = Alexandru_I._Lapedatu_sitting.png\n|order          =\n|office         = [[President of the Senate of Romania]]\n|term_start     = 16 November 1936\n|term_end       = 20 March 1937\n|monarch        = [[Carol II of Romania]]\n|predecessor    = [[Constantin Dimitriu-Dovlecel]]\n|successor      = [[Nicolae Iorga]]\n|office2        = [[Ministry of Culture and National Identity (Romania)|Ministry of Cults and Arts]]\n|term_start2    = 1923 \u2013 1926<br>1927 \u2013 1928<br>1934\n|term_end2      = 1936\n|office3        = State Minister\n|term_start3    = 1933 \u2013 1934<br>1936\n|term_end3      = 1937\n|office4        = President of the [[Romanian Academy]]\n|term_start4    = 1935\n|term_end4      = 1938\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|1876|09|14}}\n|birth_place    = Csern\u00e1tfalu, [[Austria-Hungary]] (now [[S\u0103cele|Cernatul S\u0103celelor]], [[Romania]])\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|1950|08|30|1876|09|14}}\n|death_place    = [[Sighet Prison]], [[Romanian People's Republic]]\n|citizenship=Romanian\n|nationality=Romanian\n|profession=Historian, politician\n|spouse=Victoria Pan\u0103 (1878-1965)\n|children=Ana Victoria ( Mica) (1914-1999)\n|honorific-suffix = Member of the [[Romanian Academy]]\n}}\n'''Alexandru I. Lapedatu''' (14 September 1876 \u2013 30 August 1950) was Cults and Arts and State minister of [[Romania]], [[President of the Senate of Romania]], member of the [[Romanian Academy]], its  President and General Secretary.<ref name=\":4\"/>\n\n== Early life ==\nAlexandru Lapedatu was the son of [[Ioan Alexandru Lapedatu]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Cr\u0103ciun|first=I.|date=1936|title=Alex. I. Lapedatu...|url=|journal=Omagiu|volume=|pages=XXV, XXV, XXV, XXVIII, XXVI, XXVI, XXV, XXVI, XXVII|via=}}</ref> Ph.D. of the University of [[Brussels]], Romanian poet, writer and journalist<ref>{{Cite book|title=Incerc\u0103ri...|last=Lapedatu|first=I. A.|publisher=Editura Dacia|year=1976|isbn=|editor-last=Vatamaniuc|editor-first=D. (foreword, notes)|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=}}</ref> and professor for classical languages at the Higher Greek-Orthodox Romanian College in [[Bra\u0219ov]] (today, [[Andrei \u0218aguna National College (Bra\u0219ov)|Andrei \u015eaguna National College]]).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Braharu|first=D.|date=1936|title=Ion Al. Lapedatu...|url=|journal=Omagiu|volume=|pages=VIII|via=}}</ref> Alexandru Lapedatu had a twin brother, [[Ion Lapedatu]], economist, politician and Governor of the [[National Bank of Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bnro.ro/Guvernatorii-BNR--1060.aspx|title=''Guvernatorii BNR''|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe twins became orphans when they were one and a half years old.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.memorialsighet.ro/carti/memorii-si-amintiri/|title=Memoirs and Memories|last=Lapedatu|first=I.I.|publisher=Institutul European|year=2016|isbn=978-9735860738|editor-last=Opris|editor-first=I. (foreword, notes)|edition=Internet, Civic Academy Foundation|location=Iasi|pages=25, 255, 47, 50, 55|orig-year=1998}}</ref> Their mother could only rely on a modest social help from the Bra\u0219ov municipality and some support from her family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.memorialsighet.ro/carti/alexandru-lapedatu-amintiri-2/|title=Memories|last=Lapedatu|first=Al.|publisher=Editura Albastr\u0103|year=2016|isbn=978-9739215756|editor-last=Opri\u0219|editor-first=I. (foreword, notes)|edition=Internet, Civic Academy Foundation|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=2, 90, 311, 312, 50, 59, 62, 319, 271, 117\u2013162, 195, 199, 43, 91, 205, 13, 163, 173, 164, 270|orig-year=1998}}</ref>\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu married Victoria Pan\u0103 (1878-1965) on 1 June 1911;<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":18\">{{Cite book|title=Cluj Liberals. Destinies in the Great History|last=Ciupea|first=I.|last2=\u021a\u00e2r\u0103u|first2=V.|publisher=Editura MEGA|year=2007|isbn=9789731868189|volume=Vol. 2|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=195, 195, 200\u2013201, 197, 197}}</ref> it was her second marriage, she had two children from her first marriage, Mircea and Maria Lip\u0103neanu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history-cluj.ro/Istorie/cercet/Nastasa/Aliante_familiale.htm|title=''MECANISME DE SELEC\u0162IE \u015eI INTEGRARE A ELITEI UNIVERSITARE ROM\u0102NE\u015eTI. ALIAN\u0162ELE FAMILIALE''|publisher=Institul de Istorie \"George Bari\u021biu\", Cluj|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> They had a daughter, Ana Victoria, also known as Mica (1914-1999).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Education ==\nAlexandru Lapedatu started 1883 the primary school in the village in which he was born;<ref name=\":1\" /> then he continued school in Bra\u0219ov<ref name=\":1\" /> and from 1888, after moving from Austria-Hungary to the [[Kingdom of Romania]], in [[Ia\u0219i]], where his mother remarried after the death of his father.<ref name=\":1\" /> He received his bachelor's degree from the Central College in Ia\u0219i.<ref name=\":0\" /> He studied at the Faculty of Philology and Philosophy of the [[University of Bucharest]], graduating in 1904 and getting a Diploma in Geography and History in 1910.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Professional career ==\nAlexandru Lapedatu sustained himself financially during his studies by giving private lessons<ref name=\":0\" /> or getting various jobs, like night corrector, then as columnist with the journal \u201cRom\u00e2nia Jun\u0103 / Young Romania\u201d (1899) and as a teacher for the Romanian language at the French College and the Lolliot College (1901-1903).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe started publishing national history studies already as a student, winning prizes set by University Foundation \"Carol I\" for his work on the Romanian princes [[Radu cel Frumos]] and [[Vlad C\u0103lug\u0103rul|Vlad-Vod\u0103 C\u0103lug\u0103rul]],<ref name=\":0\" /> as well as being the University laureate<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.memorialsighet.ro/carti/alexandru-lapedatu-cultura-romaneasca/|title=Alexandru Lapedatu in the Romanian Culture|last=Opri\u0219|first=I.|publisher=Editura \u0218tiin\u021bific\u0103|year=2016|isbn=978-9734401901|edition=Internet, Civic Academy Foundation|location=Bucharest|pages=15, 15, 16, 17, 39, 102, 30, 77, 31, 117, 95, 69, 57, 88, 117, 97, 99|orig-year=1996}}</ref> and the winner of the important \u201cHillel\u201d price for his work \u201c''Istoria breslelor la rom\u00e2ni''\" (\"The History of the Romanian Guilds\u201d).<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nUpon his graduation in 1903, Alexandru Lapedatu was offered an entry position as a clerk at the Library of the Romanian Academy, section for manuscripts, where he worked between 1903 and 1908;<ref name=\":2\" /> at the same time, he became a substitute professor at the [[Saint Sava National College]] in [[Bucharest]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHe was appointed Secretary of the Historic Monuments Commission in 1904, becoming a member on 12 August 1919<ref name=\":3\" /> and being then nominated President of its Transylvania section (1921 \u2013 1941).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sechel|first=D.|date=1997|title=Alexandru Lapedatu and the Research on Middle-Age...|url=http://www.diam.uab.ro/istorie.uab.ro/publicatii/colectia_bcss/bcss_3/22_sechel.pdf|journal=Universitatea '1 December 1918' Alba Iulia, Buletinul Cercurilor Stiintifice Studentesti, Arheologie-Istorie|volume=Nr. 3|pages=153|issn=1454-8097|via=}}</ref> He was elected President of the Historic Monuments Commission on 15 October 1941,<ref>{{Cite book|title=1942 Yearbook of the Historic Monuments Commission|last=Br\u0103tescu|first=V.|publisher=Monitorul Oficial \u0219i Imprimeriile Statului, Imprimeria Na\u021bional\u0103|year=1943|isbn=|location=Bucharest|pages=7}}</ref> performing this function until the Commission has been disbanded by the communist regime in 1948.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monumenteiasi.ro/pagina.php?v=despre_monumente|title=''Despre monumente''|publisher=Monumente Ia\u0219i|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu was active in a great number of commissions and associations.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was nominated secretary of the Romanian Historical Commission in 1909<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=http://www.memorialsighet.ro/carti/alexandru-lapedatu-si-contemporanii-sai/|title=Alexandru Lapedatu and His Contemporaries|last=Opri\u0219|first=I.|publisher=Editura Albastr\u0103|year=2016|isbn=978-9739215466|edition=Internet, Civic Academy Foundation|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=4, 13, 40, 16, 19, 34, 23, 32, 35, 17, 19, 4, 31, 151, 138\u2013139, 142, 147, 6|orig-year=1997}}</ref> and became member from 1911\u20131919,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pop|first=I.A.|date=2016|title=Alexandru Lapedatu : A University Profesor in Cluj|url=http://www.acad.ro/academica2002/rev2016/pag_acad2016_nr311_sep.htm|journal=Academica|volume=Anul XXVI, Nr. 9|pages=5|via=}}</ref> re-confirmed by royal decree in 1924.<ref name=\":4\" /> He was the secretary of the Committee of the \u201cSteaua\u201d Association established by [[Spiru Haret]], editing its last 27 monographs, from No. 20 to No. 47,<ref name=\":2\" /> mostly with historical content.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maz\u0103lu|first=D.M.|date=2009|title=The main periods in the writing of the historian Alexandru Lapedatu|url=https://revistatransilvania.ro/2-2009/|journal=Transilvania|volume=|pages=57|via=}}</ref> He was elected in the Society \u201cArta Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103\u201d in 1909,<ref name=\":4\" /> was an active member of the Romanian Royal Geographical Society (1915),<ref name=\":4\" /> was elected honorific member of the Romanian Numismatic Society (1920),<ref name=\":0\" /> held the Presidency of the Commission for Museum Reform in Transylvania (1921),<ref name=\":6\" /> was appointed by the Ministry of Public Education as President of the Commission for the Organization of the State Archives in Transylvania,<ref name=\":4\" /> was nominated in the Commission for Introducing National Toponyms in Transylvania, [[Banat]] and [[Partium]], in the Commission for the Verification of the Valuable Assets and Public Goods of the Previous Hungarian Monarchy and from the other territories united with the Romanian State (1922).<ref name=\":4\" /> On 9 November 1922 he was proclaimed honorific member of the Religious Historical-Archaeological Society in [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]] <ref name=\":4\" /> and he was a permanent delegate in the Committee of the [[Transylvanian Museum Society]] ({{lang-hu|Erd\u00e9lyi Muzeum Egyes\u00fclet}}) (1925).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=The Lapedatu Twins. History and Finances|last=Opri\u0219|first=I.|publisher=Oscar Print|year=2017|isbn=9789736684357|location=Bucharest|pages=111, 107, 107, 106, 53, 55, 115}}</ref>\n\nIn 1919, when the first Romanian University was established in Cluj by the {{ill|Directory Council of Transylvania|ro|Consiliul Dirigent al Transilvaniei, Banatului \u0219i \u021binuturilor rom\u00e2ne\u0219ti din Ungaria}} ({{lang-ro|Consiliul Dirigent al Transilvaniei}}), he was nominated professor for ancient Romanian history on 23 August 1919, being confirmed by the King on 28 January 1920;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=***|date=29 January 1920|title=Decree|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=Nr. 222|pages=11461|via=}}</ref> he was a member of the faculty until 1938. He was elected dean (1921-1922) and vice-dean (1922-1923) of the Philology and Philosophy Faculty<ref name=\":3\" /> and was the co-founder, together with his colleague [[Ioan Lupa\u0219]], of the Institute of National History from Cluj, today the Institute of History \"Gheorghe Bari\u021biu\" of the Romanian Academy, becoming in 1920-1938 its co-director, respectively in 1943-1945 its honorary director.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Edroiu|first=N.|date=2016|title=Alexandru Lapedatu (1876 \u2013 1950) \u2013 founder and co-director of the National History Institute in Cluj|url=http://www.acad.ro/academica2002/rev2016/pag_acad2016_nr311_sep.htm|journal=Academica|volume=Nr. 9|pages=10, 11|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu was the general director of the [[National Archives of Romania|State Archives of Romania]] (30 March 1923 - 24 March 1924).<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn parallel with his academic activities, Alexandru Lapedatu gave history conferences in [[Folk High School]]<nowiki/>s: in the Summer School in [[V\u0103lenii de Munte]], initiated in 1914 by [[Nicolae Iorga]];<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iv\u0103nescu|first=I.|date=2008|title=The Light from Valenii de Munte|url=http://www.romlit.ro/lumina_de_la_vlenii_de_munte|journal=Rom\u00e2nia Literar\u0103|volume=Nr. 31|pages=|via=|access-date=2017-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011073642/http://www.romlit.ro/lumina_de_la_vlenii_de_munte|archive-date=2017-10-11|url-status=dead}}</ref> in the University Extension in Cluj, 1925, where he is elected Honorary President;<ref name=\":3\" /> and in Free University or Folk University Association under director Sabina Cantacuzino.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=From the Life of the Ion C. Br\u0103tianu Family. 1914-1919|last=Cantacuzino|first=Sabina|publisher=Humanitas|year=2014|isbn=9789735046750|location=Bucharest|pages=295}}</ref>\n\nIn 1910 Alexandru Lapedatu was elected correspondent member<ref name=\":4\" /> and in 1918 active member of the History Section of the Romanian Academy.<ref name=\":4\" /> He was elected vice-president (1934-1935, 1938-1939), then President of the Romanian Academy (3 June 1935 \u2013 31 May 1938), and at the end of his mandate was elected its Secretary General (30 May 1939 \u2013 12 August 1948).<ref name=\":4\" /> Alexandru Lapedatu has been among the [[List of purged members of the Romanian Academy|113 members purged from the Romanian Academy]] (Decree Nr. 76 from 8 June 1948 of the communist regime).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Otiman|first=P.I.|date=2013|title=1948 \u2013 the Year of the Tremendous Sacrifice of the Romanian Academy|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/345599425/1948-anul-imensei-jertfe-a-Academiei-romane-pdf|journal=Akademos Istorie|volume=Nr. 4(31)|pages=118|via=}}</ref> The General Assembly of the Romanian Academy from 3 June 1990 reinstated his full membership.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe list of the scientific publications by Alexandru Lapedatu contains 424 titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history-cluj.ro/Istorie/Ro/Bibliografia_stiintifica.htm#LAPEDATU,%20ALEXANDRU|title=''Bibliografia \u0219tiin\u021bific\u0103''|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Political activity ==\nDescending from a family keeping \u201cstrong the awareness of the rights of the unbending man\u201d, remaining \u201ctenacious in its aspirations\u201d,<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> Alexandru Lapedatu participated already in his school years, as many of his generation, in Romanian protests and demonstrations like the ones in Ia\u0219i, in solidarity with the authors of the [[Transylvanian Memorandum|Memorandum]].<ref name=\":0\" /> During his University studies in Bucharest, he was an active member of the League for the Cultural Unity of All Romanians ({{lang-ro|Liga pentru Unitatea Cultural\u0103 a tuturor Rom\u00e2nilor}}).<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nAt the beginning of the World War I, in Bucharest, he was nominated secretary of the Support Committee for the Refugees from Transylvania, Banat and [[Bukovina]] (1914-1916).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":18\" /> In January 1918 he co-founded in [[Odessa]] the National Committee of the Romanian Refugees from Austria-Hungary that elected him as President, moved to Ia\u0219i and became a political platform bringing substantive contributions in preparing Romania for the peace negotiations at the end of World War I.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1920, Alexandru Lapedatu was nominated as member of the Coronation Commission to organize the festivities consecrating [[Ferdinand I of Romania|Ferdinand I]] as the King of all Romanians, formally closing the political process of the [[Union of Transylvania with Romania]].<ref name=\":6\" /> In 1927, upon King Ferdinand I's death, he was a member in the Senate delegation establishing the Regency and having it take the oath in front of the two Chambers of the Parliament.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHe joined the [[National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)|National Liberal Party]] in 1920, when he was elected a member of the Central Committee and of the Permanent Delegation,<ref name=\":0\" /> becoming the undeniable leader of the liberals in Transylvania.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The 'Sovereigns' of the Romanian Universities|last=Nastas\u0103|first=L.|publisher=LIMES|year=2007|isbn=978-9789737260|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=375}}</ref>\n\nAt the foundation of the new [[Babe\u0219-Bolyai University|University of Cluj]], Alexandru Lapedatu was elected as the first Senator to represent it in the Romanian Senate from 1919 to 1920.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHis first elected office as a member of the National Liberal Party was in 1922 as a member of the [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Assembly of Deputies]] from [[Ceica]] ([[Bihor County|Bihor]]). After this, he has been elected either in the Assembly of Deputies or in the Senate in all terms until 1940; he became [[Senator for life]] in 1936 and was elected President of the Romanian Senate (16 November 1936 \u2013 20 March 1937). After the royal regime had been deposed, he was elected in the Chamber of Deputies for the last time in 1946 -1947.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite book|title=Cluj Liberals. Destinies in the Great History|last=Ciupea|first=I.|last2=\u021aar\u0103u|first2=V.|publisher=Editura MEGA|year=2009|isbn=9789731868714|volume=Vol. 1|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=279, 267\u2013273}}</ref>\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu was Arts and Cults Minister in the six Governments; from 9 June 1934, while State Minister in the T\u0103t\u0103rescu (1) Government, he was also in charge of the Cults and Arts Department and the Minority Under-Secretariat of the Minister Council Presidency; in addition to his mandate, he also was as ad-interim Minister of Labour, Cooperation and Social Assurance in the Barbu \u0218tirbei Government (4-6 June 1927). He was State Minister in four Governments (the list is summarized in the following table). As State Minister for Transylvania in the [[Ion G. Duca]] Government, he co-signed the Journal of the Council of Ministers from 9 December 1927<ref>{{Cite journal|last=***|date=9 December 1933|title=Journals of the Council of Ministers|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=286 bis|pages=7644|via=}}</ref> that outlawed the fascist [[Iron Guard]]; as revenge, members of the Iron Guard assassinated Ion G. Duca on 30 December 1933. His governmental functions<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite book|title=Alexandru Lapedatu in the Romanian Culture|last=Opri\u0219|first=I.|publisher=Editura \u0218tiin\u021bific\u0103|year=1996|isbn=|edition=Paper|location=|pages=317\u2013332}}</ref> are listed in detail in the table.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| colspan=\"4\" |Government\n| colspan=\"4\" |Parliament\n|-\n|From\n|To\n|Prime minister\n|Function\n|From\n|To\n|Chamber\n|Circum-scription\n|-\n|1.12.1919\n|12.3.1920\n|Vaida-Voievod (1) (Federation)\n| \n|1919\n|1920\n|Senator\n|Uni. Cluj\n|-\n|19.1.1922\n|29.3.1926\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Ion I.C. Br\u0103tianu (6)|I. I. C. Br\u0103tianu (6)]]\n|30.10.1923:  Cults and Arts Minister\n|27.2.1922\n|27.3.1926\n|Deputy\n|Bihor\n|-\n|30.4.1926\n|4.6.1927\n|Averescu (3)\n| \n| rowspan=\"2\" |25.6.1926\n| rowspan=\"2\" |6.6.1927\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Senator\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Uni. Cluj\n|-\n|4.6.1927\n|20.6.1927\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Barbu \u0218tirbey|Stirbey]]\n|Cults and Arts Minister\n|-\n|21.6.1927\n|24.11.1927\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Ion I.C. Br\u0103tianu (7)|I. I. C. Br\u0103tianu (7)]]\n|Cults and Arts Minister\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|21.6.1927\n|9.11.1928\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Vintil\u0103 I.C. Br\u0103tianu|Vintil\u0103 Br\u0103tianu]]\n|22.6.1923:  Cults and Arts Minister\n|17.7.1927\n|10.11.1928\n|Senator\n|Bra\u0219ov\n|-\n|10.11.1928\n|6.6.1930\n|Maniu (1)\n| \n| rowspan=\"4\" |22.12.1928\n| rowspan=\"4\" |30.4.1931\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Senator\n| rowspan=\"4\" | \n|-\n|7.6.1930\n|12.6.1930\n|Mironescu (1)\n| \n|-\n|13.6.1930\n|9.10.1930\n|Maniu (2)\n| \n|-\n|10.10.1930\n|17.4.1931\n|Mironescu (2)\n| \n|-\n|18.4.1931\n|5.6.1932\n|Iorga\n| \n|15.6.1931\n|10.6.1932\n|Deputy\n|Brasov\n|-\n|6.6.1932\n|10.8.1932\n|Vaida Voievod (2)\n| \n| rowspan=\"4\" |30.7.1932\n| rowspan=\"4\" |18.11.1933\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Senator\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Uni. Cluj\n|-\n|11.8.1932\n|19.10.1932\n|Vaida Voievod (3)\n| \n|-\n|20.10.1932\n|13.1.1933\n|Maniu (3)\n| \n|-\n|14.1.1933\n|13.11.1933\n|Vaida Voievod (4)\n| \n|-\n|14.11.1933\n|29.12.1933\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Ion Gh. Duca|Duca]]\n|State Minister for Transylvania\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n|30.12.1933\n|3.1.1934\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Constantin Angelescu|Angelescu]]\n|State Minister\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n|5.1.1934\n|1.10.1934\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (1);|T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (1)]]\n|State Minister\n9.6.1934: also Cults and Arts and Minorities\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1.2.1934\n| rowspan=\"3\" |19.12.1937 \n''Since March 1936''<ref name=\":18\" />\n\n''16.11.1936-''\n\n''20.3.1937''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Senator\n''Senator for life''\n\n''President of the Senate''\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Cluj\n|-\n|2.10.1934\n|28.8.1936\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (2)|T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (2)]]\n|Cults and Arts Minister\n|-\n|29.8.1936\n|14.11.1937\n|[[:ro:Guvernul Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (3)|T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu (3)]]\n|State Minister\n|-\n|6.3.1945\n|30.11.1946\n|[[Petru Groza|Petru Groza (1)]]\n|\n|\n|\n|End of the ''Senator for life'' mandate as the Senate is abolished\n|\n|-\n|1.12.1946\n|31.12.1947\n|[[Petru Groza|Petru Groza (2)]]\n|\n|1.12.1946\n|November 1947 (the National Liberal Party is interdicted)\n|Deputy in the unicameral legislatures\n|\n|}\nAlexandru Lapedatu joined the [[National Renaissance Front]] established by [[Carol II of Romania|King Carol II of Romania]] (Royal Decree Nr. 4321 from 15 December 1938) as the only political organization legally allowed in the country;<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Teompa|first=A.\u0218.|date=2011-07-08|title=National Renaissance Front - First Mass Party|url=https://arhivaneamulromanesc.wordpress.com/dezvaluiri/teompa-aviu-stefan-%e2%80%9efrontul-renasterii-nationale-primul-partid-de-masa%e2%80%9c/|journal=Neamul Rom\u00e2nesc-on-line|volume=|pages=|issn=1844-055X|via=}}</ref> Carol II transformed the Front into the Party of the Nation (Royal Decree Nr. 2056 from 22 June 1940) that was disbanded by the prime minister [[Ion Antonescu]] (Decree of 9 September 1940) three days after Carol's abdication.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nAfter [[King Michael's Coup|King Michael's Coup d'\u00e9tat]] from 23 August 1944 that removed Ion Antonescu from power, the political parties prepared to re-enter the political life and Alexandru Lapedatu assumed leadership for the effort of the [[National Liberal Party-Br\u0103tianu]] in Transylvania<ref name=\":17\" /> (a [[National Liberal Party\u2013T\u0103t\u0103rescu|parallel effort]] with the same objective was led by [[Gheorghe T\u0103t\u0103r\u0103scu]]). Alexandru Lapedatu entered in some circumscriptions in Transylvania in an electoral cartel with the [[Peasants' Party (Romania)|Peasants' Party]] obtaining a modest and ephemeral electoral success in the [[1946 Romanian general elections|elections from 19 November 194]]6, when two candidates were elected: Lapedatu in Cluj and {{ill|Vasile Netea|ro}} in [[Satu Mare]], in spite of the tremendous pressure and falsifications perpetrated by the {{ill|Bloc of Democratic Parties|ro|Blocul Partidelor Democrate}} dominated by the Communists.<ref name=\":4\" /> He soon recognized that the communist repression would prevail, but did not give up hope: on 30 September 1949, it was reported to the [[Securitate]] that Alexandru Lapedatu \u201cbelieves in the future of the nation and in the capitulation of Russia and of communism\u201d.<ref name=\":4\" /> His vision has been confirmed more than 50 years later, with the fall of the [[Berlin Wall]].\n\n=== International missions ===\nIn 1917, the [[Central Powers]] armies occupied Bucharest and were advancing towards Ia\u0219i. The Romanian Government decided to move the [[Romanian Treasure|State Treasury]] to Russia in two transports, delegating Alexandru Lapedatu to accompany the second one that included cultural goods.<ref name=\":3\" /> He left Ia\u0219i for [[Moscow]] on 28 July 1917, and stayed there until 19 December 1917, experiencing the arrival of the [[October Revolution|Bolshevik revolution]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu was a member of the Romanian delegation to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference (1919)]],<ref name=\":2\" /> participating in the negotiations on three instances: December 1918 - June 1919, returning after taking part in the signature ceremony of the [[Treaty of Versailles]]; again July \u2013 August 1919 participating in the incipient phase of the negotiations concerning [[Bessarabia]];<ref name=\":0\" /> and finally December 1919 - March 1920, contributing to the negotiations with [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u20131946)|Hungary]] that will be concluded by the [[Treaty of Trianon]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 31 March 1922, he was nominated as a delegate and technical adviser in the Romanian Delegation to the [[Genoa Conference (1922)|Genoa Economic and Financial Conference]] (10 April - 19 May 1922) in which representatives from 34 nations addressed the [[Europe]] restoration in the aftermath of [[World War I]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu was a member of the Romanian delegation to the XXXV [[Inter-Parliamentary Union|Inter-Parliamentary Conference]], Oslo, 15\u201319 August 1939, one of the last efforts to secure peace just a few days before the beginning of the [[World War II]].<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n=== Romanian Participation in the Paris Peace Conference (1919) ===\nAlexandru Lapedatu engaged politically in working for the Romanian unity in 1918, as President of the National Committee of the Romanian Refugees from Austria-Hungary, established in Odessa on 21 January 1918,<ref name=\":0\" /> then moved to Ia\u0219i, that pursued the political unity of all Romanians<ref name=\":2\" /> and intended to represent them in [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]]'s Nationality Association in [[Kiev]]. Through this Committee, Lapedatu connected with key political personalities in Romania and, thanks to the support from the French Ambassador, the Count of Saint-Aulaire, with the [[Triple Entente]]'s representatives.<ref name=\":0\" /> On 6 / 19 October the Committee issued a Declaration, distributed to all political actors including [[Ferdinand I of Romania|King Ferdinand I]], contesting the manifesto of [[Charles I of Austria]] proclaiming the federalization of the Empire and demanding that all territories inhabited by Romanians be united with Romania.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\nExperiencing the depressing installation of a German Mission in Ia\u0219i as a consequence of the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)]], Alexandru Lapedatu published the paper \u201c''Chestiunea transilvan\u0103''\" (\"The Transylvanian Issue\") in ''Neamul Rom\u00e2nesc'', stating that the Romanian issue shall find its solution when the situation of all nationalities will be addressed at the peace negotiations at the end of the war, expected to happen soon.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn his letter from 28 June 1918 to the President of the National Liberal Party, [[Ion I. C. Br\u0103tianu]], Alexandru Lapedatu expressed the urgent need for a document summarizing the Romanian position in the political evolution to be expected in the near future, specifically addressing: 1) the geographical, ethnical, social, cultural and political situation of the Romanians in relationship with the other nationalities; 2) the historical and political evolution between Romanians and Hungarians; 3) the denationalization policies in Transylvania and Bukovina; and 4) the impossibility to implement autonomy, federalization and the unavoidable dismantling of the Danube monarchy to create new national states.<ref name=\":18\" /> In recognition to his competence, Alexandru Lapedatu was nominated between 1919 and 1922 as an expert in the Romanian delegation to the Paris Peace Conference (1918);<ref name=\":2\" /> the documents he authored were submitted by Romania to the Conference and were used by the Romanian Delegation as basis for the negotiations.<ref>{{Cite book|title=La Roumanie devant le Congr\u00e8s de la Paix|last=Lapedatu|first=Alexandru|publisher=Ed. Dubois et Bauer|year=1919|isbn=|volume=4 volumes|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref>\n\n=== The Cultural Policy in the United Romania ===\nAlexandru Lapedatu had cultural activities in various associations and foundations, such as in the [[Asocia\u021bia Transilvan\u0103 pentru Literatura Rom\u00e2n\u0103 \u0219i Cultura Poporului Rom\u00e2n|Asocia\u021bia Transilvan\u0103 pentru Literatura Rom\u00e2n\u0103 \u0219i Cultura Poporului Rom\u00e2n (ASTRA)]] / Transylvanian Association for the Romanian Literature and the Culture of the Romanian People<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|url=http://centrulslavici.uvvg.ro/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/G.%20Preda%20ACTIVITATEA%20ASTRA%201918-1943.pdf|title='Astra' Activity in the 25 Years since the Union (1918-1943)|last=Preda|first=G.|publisher=Editura ASTRA|year=1944|isbn=|location=Sibiu|pages=4, 81, 89, 70, 83\u201384, 113, 168}}</ref> that proclaimed him honorific member of (8/9 November 1924)<ref name=\":20\" /> and elected him member of the \"demographic and ethnology-politic section\" (14/15 September 1935).<ref name=\":20\" /> For ASTRA he provided funding,<ref name=\":20\" /> held conferences,<ref name=\":20\" /> supported the publication of the ASTRA library,<ref name=\":20\" /> and donated the Fund \u201cAl. I. Lapedatu\u201d.<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu expressed his conviction that promoting the cultural development is an essential mission of the State and the nation, and proposed and implemented policies pursuing the enhancement of the cultural and artistic prestige of all cities, and of the country as a whole.<ref name=\":3\" />  Alexandru Lapedatu formulated the principles of the monument preservation and restoration already in 1911.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Brief Overview on the Historic Monuments Conservation and Restoration in Romania|last=Lapedatu|first=Al.|work=In: \"To Spiru C. Haret. Yours from Yours\"|publisher=Tip. Carol G\u00f6bl \u2013 I.St. Rasidescu|year=1911|isbn=|location=Bucharest|pages=780\u2013801}}</ref> Under his leadership, the Section of the Historical Monuments Commission in Cluj executed in 1929-1948 more than 240 conservation and restoration projects, addressing Romanian heritage such as antiques [[Roman Empire|Roman]] and [[Dacia]]n vestiges, medieval stone churches and monasteries, wooden architecture, rear glass painted icons, the [[Hunedoara]] and [[Bran Castle|Bran]] Castles, the \u0218u\u021bu Palace and the Filipescu House in Bucharest etc.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite book|title=Selected Publications|last=Lapedatu|first=A.|publisher=Editura Dacia|year=1985|isbn=|editor-last=Opri\u0219|editor-first=I.|location=Cluj-Napoca|pages=32, 27, 37}}</ref> After 1918, the Commission for Historic Monuments also undertook large restoration works on monuments belonging to Hungarian or [[Transylvanian Saxons|Saxon]] minorities including Roman Catholic or Evangelical churches in Cluj-Napoca, [[Sibiu]], Brasov, [[Alba Iulia]], [[Sighi\u0219oara]] etc.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Commission of Historic Monuments|last=Opri\u0219|first=I.|publisher=Editura Enciclopedica|year=1994|isbn=9789734500772|location=Bucharest|pages=166}}</ref>\n\nAs Cults and Arts Minister for almost seven years, he pursued a wide the areas of activities:\n* He initiated and/or supported the establishment of museums in Bucharest (National Pinacoteca, \u201c[[Theodor Aman]]\u201d, \u201c[[Ioan Kalinderu|Kalinderu]]\u201d, \u201c[[:ro:Anastase Simu|Simu]]\u201d); in Cluj-Napoca ([[Ethnographic Museum of Transylvania|Ethnographic Museum]], Museum of the Romanian Language, the [[National Museum of Romanian History|National History Museum]]);<ref name=\":3\" /> in [[Avram Iancu, Alba|Vidra]] (\u201c[[Avram Iancu]]\u201d Museum);<ref name=\":3\" /> in [[Drobeta-Turnu Severin|Turnu Severin]] (remains of the [[Trajan]]\u2019s bridge across the Danube built by [[Apollodorus of Damascus|Apollodorus]]); in Alba Iulia (Museum of the Union), in [[Constan\u021ba|Constanta]] (Dobrogea Museum);<ref name=\":3\" /> as well as in many other cities among which [[Turda]], [[Sighi\u0219oara|Sighisoara]], [[Oradea]], [[Arad, Romania|Arad]], Sighetu Marmatiei, [[Timi\u0219oara|Timisoara]], [[Dej]], [[B\u0103ile Herculane|Herculane]], [[Caransebe\u0219]], [[T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]], [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmisegetuza]], [[N\u0103s\u0103ud]], [[Bistri\u021ba]], Bra\u0219ov, [[F\u0103g\u0103ra\u0219]], [[Blaj]], [[Sibiu]], [[Zal\u0103u]], Satu Mare,<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Deva, Romania|Deva]], [[Piatra Neam\u021b]] etc.<ref name=\":21\" />\n* He supported financially and participated in the unveiling of public monuments dedicated to Romanian historic and cultural personalities among which [[Gheorghe Laz\u0103r]] (Cluj, 1924); Avram Iancu ([[Baia de Cri\u0219|Baia de Cris]], 1924); [[Ion Creang\u0103]], [[Nicolae Beldiceanu|Nicolae N. Beldiceanu]], [[Dimitrie Anghel]], [[Nicolae Gane]] and [[Barbu \u0218tef\u0103nescu Delavrancea]] (Ia\u0219i, 1924);<ref name=\":3\" /> [[:ro:Ioan Mihaly de Ap\u0219a|Ioan Mihaly of Ap\u0219a]] (Sighetu Marmatiei, 1925); [[Stephen III of Moldavia|Stephen The Great]] ([[Chi\u0219in\u0103u]], 1925); [[Michael the Brave]] (1926, [[Gurusl\u0103u River|Guruslau]], dismantled in 1940 by the Hungarian authorities);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.graiulsalajului.ro/istoria-monumentului-de-la-guruslu-a-43937|title=The History of the Guruslau Monument|last=Farkas|first=E.|date=|website=Graiul S\u0103lajului|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [[Bogdan Petriceicu Hasdeu|B.P. Hasdeu]] (1927); [[Dimitrie Onciul|D. Onciul]] (1927); [[Vasile Alecsandri]] (mausoleum in [[Mirce\u0219ti|Mircesti]], 1928);<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Revolt of Horea, Clo\u0219ca and Cri\u0219an|Horia, Closca and Crisan]] ([[Alba Iulia]] 1929); Barbu \u0218tef\u0103nescu Delavrancea (Oradea, 1934); [[Ecaterina Teodoroiu]] ([[T\u00e2rgu Jiu]], 1935); [[Vasile Lucaciu]] (Satu Mare, 1935); Spiru Haret (1940) etc.<ref name=\":21\" />\n* To stimulate the development of the national culture, Alexandru Lapedatu as Minister of Cults and Arts institutes in 1925 the National Awards for Culture and Arts.<ref name=\":3\" /> Considering that establishing theatrical institutions in the national language is a moral duty in the new provinces, a direct contribution to the cultural unification, he collaborates with the dramatic authors, actors, directors and producers, submits to the Parliament for adoption and signs the Lege pentru organizarea si administrarea teatrelor nationale si controlul spectacolelor in Romania / Law Regarding the Organization and Administration of the National Theaters and the Performances Control in Romania adopted by the Parliament on 21 March 1926,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=***|date=21 March 1926|title=Law Regarding the Organization and Administration of the National Theaters and the Performances Control in Romania|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=No. 67|pages=3912\u20133920|via=}}</ref> establishing a safety net for the artists, with payment, retirement, litigation and other rights, and the obligation to show original plays in Romanian language, completing the repertoire with international works.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== The General Regime of the Cults in Romania (1928 \u2013 1948) ===\nThe first challenging task of Alexandru Lapedatu as a minister has been to establish a legal frame for the cults in the unified Romania.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=\u0218tirban|first=M.|date=2002|title=The Issue of a Reglementation for the General Regime of the Cults (1922-1928)|url=http://www.history-cluj.ro/Istorie/anuare/2002/Stirban%20-%20Problema%20reglementarii.htm|journal=Submission to the Yearly Yearbook of the History Institute \"George Bari\u0163iu\", Series HISTORICA|volume=Nr. XLI|pages=|via=}}</ref> He presented the statement of reasons for the law clarifying that in the united Romania, besides the Orthodox Church, the State recognized the following cults: Romanian Greek-Catholic (united), Catholic (of Latin, Greek and Armenian ritual), reformed (Calvin), evangelic-Lutheran, Unitarian, Mosaic, Muslim and finally Baptist (recognized only in Transylvania), each governed by a different legislation in the regions coming from Russia, [[Austria]], Hungary, [[Bulgaria]] respectively the Kingdom of Romania.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Our Church and the Minority Cults...|last=Russu Ardeleanu|first=D.|publisher=Imprimeria ziarului \"Universul\"|year=1928|isbn=|location=Bucharest|pages=14\u201315}}</ref> The framework was set by the Constitution from 1923 that guaranteed absolute freedom of consciousness and equal treatment for all cults, except that it stipulated that the Orthodox Church was dominant, and the Greek-catholic cult has priority.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=29 March 1923|title=CONSTITUTION|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=No. 282|pages=13318|via=}}</ref>\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu worked towards a legislation reinforcing the State sovereignty and secularism.\n* First, he proposed a law to elevate the status of the head of Romanian Orthodox Church to the rank of a Patriarch; it was adopted by the Parliament on 25 February 1925, with his signature as the responsible minister;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=25 February 1925|title=Law to Elevate the Arch-Bishop and Metropolitan Siege of Ungro-Vlahia as the Primate of Romania to the Rank of Patriarch|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=No. 44|pages=1921\u20131922|via=}}</ref>\n* Second, he worked with the Orthodox Church to define its Statute unifying the differences among the different regions; upon his proposal, the Parliament adopted the Statute by the law from 6 May 1925, with his signature as the responsible minister;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6 May 1925|title=Law Regarding the Organization of the Romanian Orthodox Church|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=44|pages=4993\u20135015|via=}}</ref>\n* Third, he collaborated with the Ministry of Foreign Affairs to restart the negotiations on a Concordat with the [[Holy See]] and concluded them on 15 January 1926 when an official text was agreed upon by both parties;<ref name=\":0\" /> the Concordat was signed on 10 May 1927 and ratified on 12 June 1929.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gojinescu|first=C.|date=2009|title=The Concordate from 1928 ...|url=http://www.etnosfera.ro/pdf/2009/1/03.pdf|journal=Etnosfera|volume=No. 1, Anul I (XII)|pages=25\u201337|via=}}</ref>\nSince the two exceptions mentioned in the Constitution were no more in the position to challenge State prerogatives, it was now possible for Alexandru Lapedatu to submit to the Parliament, after animated consultations and debates, a project that obtained almost the unanimity of votes both in the Chamber of Deputy and in the Senate; it was adopted on 22 April 1928<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=22 April 1929|title=LEGEA PENTRU REGIMUL GENERAL AL CULTELOR / LAW FOR THE GENERAL REGIME OF THE CULTS|url=|journal=Official Journal|volume=Nr 89|pages=|via=}}</ref> and remained in power until 1948.<ref name=\":22\" /> It was an essential achievement toward the unification of the young Romanian State.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\n==Death==\nIn 1950, the communist regime cancelled the pension of Alexandru Lapedatu, leaving him without any revenue.<ref name=\":4\" /> He was arrested in the night of 5/6 May 1950 in the so-called \"group of dignitaries\u201d. He passed away on 30 August 1950 in the [[Sighet Prison]] and was buried in an unmarked common grave.<ref name=\":4\" /> His cenotaph is in the \"Groaveri\" cemetery in Bra\u0219ov.\n\n== Distinctions ==\nAlexandru Lapedatu received national and foreign distinctions:<ref name=\":23\" />\n\n'''[[Orders, decorations, and medals of Romania|National distinctions]]:'''\n* Jubilee medal Carol I, Royal decree Nr. 5384/28, December 1905. Official Journal Nr. 218 / 1 January 1906 \u2013 10 May 1906\n* Order of Bene Merenti of the Royal House, Grade: Officer or 2nd Class, Royal Decree Nr. 885/24 March 1909\n* [[Order of the Star of Romania]], Grade: Commander, Royal Decree from 21 October 1922\n* [[Order of the Crown (Romania)]], Grade: Grand Cross, Royal Decree from 22 January 1926\n* Order of Bene Merenti of the Royal House, Grade: Commander or 1st Class, Royal Decree Nr. 2749/ 3 November 1928 for achievements in the fields of \u201chistory, literature and education\u201d\n* Medal \u201cThe Reward for the Work in Education\u201d,  First Class, Royal Decree Nr. 4102 / 17 November 1930 \u201cfor services in the field of education\u201d\n* Honorific Sign \"The Reward for the Work in the Public Service\" for 25 years, Royal Decree Nr. 3994 / 10 December 1931\n* The Order \"The Cultural Merit\" for literature, Grade: Officer or First Class, Royal Decree from 22 September 1931 \u201cfor services brought to education and religion, as well as contributions in the field of literature, arts, sciences and social endeavours\u201d\n* The \u201cPele\u0219\u201d Medal, established by Royal Decree Nr. 2305 / 16 August 1933; awarded: Decree Nr. 224 / 25 September 1933\n* Honorific Sign \u201c[[Eagle of Romania]]\u201d, Grade:  Commander of Second Class, Royal Decree Nr. 2762 / 11 November 1933\n* Order of Ferdinand I, Grade: Knight, Royal Decree from 15 March 1934\n* Medal for the Centenary of King Carol I / Medalia Centenarul Regelui Carol I, Royal Decree Nr. 1915, 2036 / 1939 and Nr. 372 / 1940 \n* \u201cFor contributions to the army supply\u201d, Brevet issued by the Ministry of Supply / Ministerul inzestrarii armatei, Nr. 6272 / p March 1940\n* \u201cCultural Merit\u201d Order and Medal, Grade: Commander, Royal Decree Nr. 248 / 1 February 1943 \u201cfor literature\u201d\n'''Foreign :'''\n* The Cross of Merit of the [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|Holy Sepulchre]] with Collar, Jerusalem, decree Nr. 68 / 26 Jan. 1924\n* Order of [[Order of Polonia Restituta|Polonia Restituta]],  class: Grand Cross, 1925\n* Medal of the National Order of the [[Legion of Honour]], grade: Commander, Paris, decree Nr. 56608 / 19 Dec 1927\n* [[Order of the Crown of Italy]], grade: Great Cross, Chancellery of Orders nr. 1067 / 8 June. 1928\n* [[Order of St. Gregory the Great]], Grade: Great Cross (civilian), Pontifical Decree of Pius XI / 10 September 1929\n* [[Order of the White Lion]], Grade: Great Cross, Decree of the Czechoslovakia President, 1937\n* [[Order of the Yugoslav Crown]], Grade: Great Cross, Decree Nr. 1116 / 20 Feb. 1937\n\n== Legacy ==\nStreets in Romania named after Alexandru Lapedatu:\n* Alexandru Lapedatu Alley, [[Cluj-Napoca]]\n* Alexandru Ion Lapedatu Street, [[Bra\u0219ov]]\n* Alexandru Ion Lapedatu Street, [[S\u0103cele]]\n\nAlexandru Lapedatu donated his library to the [[Central University Library of Cluj-Napoca]]; he is listed in the Golden Book of donors and the Professors\u2019 Reading Hall is named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bcucluj.ro/ro/despre-noi/dona%C5%A3ii-%C5%9Fi-donatori-de-prestigiu|title=''Donatori de prestigiu''|publisher=\u201cLucian Blaga\u201d Central University Library|language=Romanian|accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis bust is placed in front of the \u201cAlexandru Lapedatu\u201d Cultural Establishment in the European College Foundation in Cluj-Napoca.\n\nHis name is on plaques on his native house in S\u0103cele, in the National College Andrei \u0218aguna and in the National College Saint Sava.\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* ***: Official Journal / Monitorul Oficial Nr. 222/29 January 1920, Decree, pag. 11461\n* ***: Official Journal / Monitorul Oficial Nr. 282, 29 March 1923,\u201cCONSTITUTIUNE / CONSTITUTION\u201d, pag. 13315-13333\n* ***: Official Journal / Monitorul Oficial Nr. 44, 25 February 1925, \u201cLege pentru Ridicarea Scaunului Arhiepiscopal si Mitropolitan al Ungro-Vlahiei ca Primat al Romaniei, la rangul de Scaun Patriarhal / Law to Elevate the Arch-Bishop and Metropolitan Siege of Ungro-Vlahia as the Primate of Romania to the Rank of Patriarch\u201d, pag. 1921-1922\n* ***: Official Journal / Monitorul Oficial Nr. 97, 6 May 1925, \u201cLege pentru organizarea Bisericii Ortodoxe rom\u00e2ne / Law Regarding the Organization of the Romanian Orthodox Church\u201d, pag. 4993-5015\n* ***: Official Journal / Monitorul Oficial Nr. 67, 21 March 1926, \u201cLege pentru organizarea \u0219i administrarea teatrelor na\u021bionale \u0219i controlul spec